definitions: move at a faster speed than someone or something else in a race or chase
successfully escape from danger or pursuit by running away quickly
examples: The cheetah can outrun any other land animal on Earth
She trained hard to outrun her competitors in the marathon
The thieves tried to outrun the police through the busy streets
We barely managed to outrun the storm before it hit

definitions: obtain goods or services from an outside supplier rather than producing them internally within a company
examples: Many tech companies outsource their customer service to reduce costs
The hospital decided to outsource its cafeteria services this year

definitions: exceed something else in weight when measured on a scale
be greater or more significant in value importance or influence than something else
examples: The large elephant outweighs three adult horses put together
This suitcase outweighs the airline's baggage limit by five pounds
The benefits of exercise far outweigh any temporary discomfort
Her experience outweighs her lack of formal education for this position

definitions: defeat or get the better of someone by being cleverer or using superior intelligence
examples: The detective managed to outwit the criminal with careful planning
She outwitted her opponents in the chess tournament through strategy

definitions: give someone or something too much to carry deal with or think about
examples: Don't overburden yourself with too many responsibilities at once
The old bridge was overburdened by heavy trucks passing daily

definitions: take an excessive and dangerous amount of a drug or medicine either accidentally or intentionally
examples: The patient accidentally overdosed on pain medication last night
Many musicians have tragically overdosed on prescription drugs over years

definitions: drive or work something too hard beyond its normal capacity or recommended limits
examples: Don't overdrive the engine or you'll damage it permanently
She tends to overdrive herself during busy seasons at work

definitions: form too high an estimate of the size amount or importance of something
examples: Many people overestimate their ability to multitask effectively at work
The contractor overestimated the cost of renovating our kitchen significantly

definitions: flow over the brim or edges of a container when too full
be so full that contents cannot be contained and must spill out
examples: The bathtub will overflow if you don't turn off the tap
Heavy rain caused the river to overflow its banks yesterday
The parking lot overflowed with cars during the holiday shopping season
Her heart overflowed with joy when she saw her grandchildren

definitions: stick out or extend beyond something else especially projecting from above
examples: The cliff overhangs the beach creating shade for swimmers below
Tree branches overhang the fence into our neighbor's yard

definitions: take apart examine and repair something thoroughly to improve its condition and performance
examples: The mechanic will overhaul the engine to fix all problems
The company decided to overhaul its outdated computer systems completely

definitions: accidentally hear a conversation or remark not intended for you to hear
examples: I couldn't help but overhear their argument in the restaurant
She overheard her coworkers discussing the surprise party they planned

definitions: make or become too hot to function properly or safely
examples: The laptop tends to overheat when running demanding software programs
Don't let the engine overheat by driving without enough coolant

definitions: extend over and cover a part of something else physically
occur at the same time or have something in common with another event
examples: The roof tiles overlap to prevent rain from getting through
These two carpet pieces overlap slightly in the middle
Our vacation plans overlap with the busy season at work
The responsibilities of these two positions overlap quite a bit

definitions: cover something with a layer or coating of something else on top
examples: The designer will overlay the image with text for the poster
They decided to overlay the old floor with new hardwood

definitions: put too much electrical current through a circuit causing it to fail
give someone more work or information than they can handle effectively
examples: Don't overload the circuit by plugging in too many appliances
The truck was overloaded with cargo beyond its weight limit
Teachers shouldn't overload students with homework during exam week
The website crashed because we overloaded the server with requests

definitions: defeat or overcome someone by using greater strength or force
examples: The security guards managed to overpower the intruder quickly
The strong smell of paint overpowered all other scents

definitions: use one's authority to reject or cancel someone else's decision or order
interrupt an automatic function to take manual control of a system
examples: The manager can override the cashier's decision about returns
Congress voted to override the president's veto on the bill
You need to override the security system to open this door
The pilot had to override the autopilot during the storm

definitions: reject or disallow someone's decision or objection by using higher authority
examples: The judge decided to overrule the lawyer's objection immediately
The board of directors can overrule the CEO's decision

definitions: spread over or occupy a place in large numbers especially harmfully
go beyond a planned cost time or limit in a project
examples: Weeds have overrun the garden since we went on vacation
The abandoned house was overrun with rats and insects
The construction project overrun its budget by two million dollars
The meeting overrun by an hour due to heated discussions

definitions: tower above and cast a shadow over something smaller below
cause someone or something to seem less important or impressive by comparison
examples: The tall buildings overshadow the small park in the city
Dark clouds overshadowed the mountain peaks all afternoon
His recent scandal overshadowed all his previous achievements
The tragedy overshadowed what should have been a celebration

definitions: go past or beyond a target point limit or destination unintentionally
examples: The plane overshot the runway and had to circle back
Be careful not to overshoot your budget this month

definitions: catch up with and pass another vehicle or person while traveling
come upon someone suddenly or unexpectedly especially of events or feelings
examples: The sports car overtook three vehicles on the highway
She trained hard to overtake the leading runner
Fear overtook him as he entered the dark abandoned house
Sleep finally overtook the exhausted traveler at midnight

definitions: remove forcibly from power especially a government or leader through rebellion
examples: The rebels attempted to overthrow the dictator last year
The military coup successfully overthrew the elected government

definitions: turn something over so that it is upside down or on its side
officially decide that a legal decision or judgment is wrong and change it
examples: Strong winds overturned several boats in the harbor yesterday
The toddler accidentally overturned his bowl of cereal
The appeals court decided to overturn the original verdict
New evidence may overturn the conviction from ten years ago

definitions: use something too much or too often causing harm damage or reduced effectiveness
examples: Athletes who overuse their muscles risk serious injury
Don't overuse antibiotics or they'll become less effective

definitions: defeat someone or something by using great force or superior numbers
have a strong emotional effect on someone making them unable to think clearly
examples: The army was overwhelmed by enemy forces on all sides
Don't overwhelm the new employee with too much information
Grief overwhelmed her when she heard the tragic news
The beauty of the sunset overwhelmed us into complete silence

definitions: spend the winter in a particular place especially of animals birds or plants
examples: Many birds overwinter in warmer southern regions every year
These plants can overwinter outdoors in mild climates only

definitions: cause someone to work too hard or too long damaging their health
examples: The company tends to overwork its employees during busy seasons
Don't overwork yourself preparing for the presentation tomorrow

definitions: combine chemically with oxygen especially causing metal to corrode or rust
examples: Iron will oxidize and form rust when exposed to moisture
The copper statue oxidized to a green color over time

definitions: calm someone who is angry or upset by making them quiet or satisfied
examples: The mother tried to pacify her crying baby with a bottle
The government attempted to pacify protesters with policy changes

definitions: propel a boat through water using a paddle with short strokes
hit someone especially a child with a flat implement as punishment
examples: We love to paddle our canoe across the lake at sunset
The kayakers paddled against the strong river current
Some schools used to paddle students for breaking rules
The coach threatened to paddle players who missed practice

definitions: fasten or secure something with a detachable lock that hangs from what it secures
examples: Remember to padlock the shed before leaving for vacation
The school will padlock the gates after hours for security

definitions: become less interesting or enjoyable through being experienced too much or too long
examples: The excitement of city life began to pall after several years
Even the best food will pall if eaten every single day

definitions: do or provide what someone wants even though it may be wrong or harmful
examples: Politicians often pander to voters instead of addressing real issues
The media shouldn't pander to the public's appetite for scandal

definitions: ask people for money in a public place especially on the street
examples: People often panhandle near the subway station during rush hour
The city passed laws against panhandling in tourist areas

definitions: express or represent something using gestures and body movements without words
examples: The actor had to pantomime being trapped in an invisible box
She tried to pantomime directions when they didn't speak her language

definitions: drop from an aircraft using a parachute to slow descent and land safely
examples: The soldiers will parachute behind enemy lines at dawn
She learned to parachute during her military training last summer

definitions: be similar or corresponding to something in features development or comparison
examples: His career path parallels that of his famous mentor closely
The growth in online shopping parallels the decline in retail stores

definitions: cause a person or body part to lose the ability to move or feel
make someone or something unable to function act or move normally
examples: The accident temporarily paralyzed his legs below the knee
The snake's venom can paralyze its prey within minutes
Fear can paralyze people preventing them from making decisions
The strike threatened to paralyze the city's transportation system

definitions: express the meaning of something using different words especially to achieve greater clarity
examples: Students must paraphrase the author's ideas in their own words
Can you paraphrase this complex legal document in simple terms

definitions: divide something into parts or portions to distribute or deal with separately
examples: The land was parceled out among the farmer's three children
They parceled the work among team members based on expertise

definitions: forgive or excuse a person for an offense or wrongdoing especially officially
examples: The governor decided to pardon several non-violent offenders last month
Please pardon my interruption but this matter is urgent

definitions: remove the outer layer or edge from something by cutting with a knife
examples: She carefully pared the apple before making the pie
Use a sharp knife to pare the thick skin from the mango

definitions: hold a conference between opposing sides especially enemies to discuss terms
examples: The two warring nations agreed to parley for peace terms
The pirates wanted to parley with the captain about ransom

definitions: produce a humorous imitation of something especially to mock or ridicule it
examples: The comedy show loves to parody popular television commercials
The students decided to parody their teacher's mannerisms

definitions: release a prisoner temporarily before the completion of their sentence on promise of good behavior
examples: The board decided to parole him after serving half his sentence
They will parole the inmate if she meets all requirements

definitions: repeat mechanically without thought or understanding like a parrot mimics speech
examples: Children often parrot what they hear adults say at home
Don't just parrot the textbook answer explain it yourself

definitions: ward off a weapon or attack with a countermove especially in fencing or boxing
examples: The fencer skillfully parried every thrust from her opponent
He learned to parry punches during his boxing training

definitions: analyze a sentence into its parts and describe their grammatical roles
examine or analyze something in detail to understand it better
examples: Students must parse complex sentences in their grammar class
The software can parse code to identify syntax errors
Let's parse the contract carefully before signing anything important
Researchers parsed the data looking for meaningful patterns
